  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use propositional logic only when your statements can be treated as true/false without internal structure.\n¶Definitions A propositional language has atomic propositions p,q,rp,q,r and connectives like ∧,∨,⇒,¬\\wedge,\\vee,\\Rightarrow,\\neg. A valuation assigns each atomic proposition a truth value. ¶Vocabulary (plain language) Atomic proposition: a basic statement with no logical parts. Connective: a symbol that combines propositions. Valuation: a truth assignment to atoms. ¶Symbols used ∧\\wedge: and ∨\\vee: or ⇒\\Rightarrow: implies ¬\\neg: not ¶Intuition Propositional logic treats each statement as a black box that is either true or false. Logic then tells you how compound statements depend on the truth of their parts.\n",
